            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> It seems more intuitive if (transitively) cimported declarations came in one block, rather than being subject to the early-late split.\r\n\r\nSo if I understand you correctly, there shouldn't be an early/late split at all, declarations (for anything: both extern and non-extern declarations) should appear in the generated C file in the order that they appear in the sources (whatever that means)?\r\n\r\nMy use case is essentially a `.pxd` file containing\r\n```\r\ncdef void foo \"foo\"()  # Implemented in the corresponding .pyx file\r\n\r\ncdef extern from \"something.h\":\r\n   void extern_function_calling_foo()  # Calls foo()\r\n```\r\nand the same for `cdef` variables instead of functions. So I guess that your proposal would work for me.\r\n\r\nNow the practical question becomes: how realistic is it to actually implement that? As you know, I would be really disappointed if this feature would be dropped for Cython 0.28 and postponed until \"whenever\".",
